Plotting Conditional Summaries

Notes:

pf.fc_by_age_gender <- group_by(pf, age, gender) %>% 
  summarize(mean_friend_count = mean(friend_count), 
            median_friend_count = median(friend_count),
            n = n())

ggplot(aes(x = age, y = median_friend_count),
       data = subset(pf.fc_by_age_gender, !is.na(gender))) + 
  geom_line(aes(color=gender))

Thinking in Ratios

Notes:

Wide and Long Format

Notes: If long includes repeated and discrete variables like age or gender, it is useful at times to create new dfs that aggregate these data with calculated parameters like median or mean. Categorical variables like gender are simply counted up in the wide format. ***

Reshaping Data

Notes:

library(reshape2)
## 
## Attaching package: 'reshape2'
## The following object is masked from 'package:tidyr':
## 
##     smiths
pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide <- dcast(data = pf.fc_by_age_gender, 
                                  age ~ gender,
                                  value.var = "median_friend_count")
pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide$ratio <- 
  pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide$male/pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide$female
pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide <- subset(
  pf.fc_by_age_gender[c('age', 'gender', 'median_friend_count')], 
  !is.na(gender)) %>% 
  spread(gender, median_friend_count) %>% 
  mutate(ratio = male / female)

Ratio Plot

Notes: The linetype parameter can take the values 0-6: 0 = blank, 1 = solid, 2 = dashed 3 = dotted, 4 = dotdash, 5 = longdash 6 = twodash

ggplot(data = pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide, aes(x=age, y=female/male)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, linetype = 2, alpha=0.5)

Third Quantitative Variable

Notes:

pf$year_joined <- floor(2014-pf$tenure/365)

Cut a Variable

Notes: Pretty pandas-like

pf$year_joined.bucket <- cut(pf$year_joined, c(2004, 2009, 2011, 2012, 2014), labels = c("2004-2009", "2009-2011", "2011-2012", "2012-2014"))

table(pf$year_joined.bucket, useNA = "ifany")

## 2004-2009 2009-2011 2011-2012 2012-2014      <NA> 
##      6669     15308     33366     43658         2

Plot the Grand Mean

Bias-Variance Tradeoff Revisited

Notes:

ggplot(aes(x = tenure, y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure >= 1)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = 'summary',
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 7 * round(tenure / 7), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 30 * round(tenure / 30), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 90 * round(tenure / 90), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun.y = mean)

Sampling Observations

Notes: With so many repeat measurements it is useful to take a random subset of the data (in this case purchases for a household), to be able to more closely examine variation across data points (households). ***

Looking at Samples of Households

set.seed(4230)
samp.ids <- sample(levels(yo$id), 16)

ggplot(data=subset(yo, id %in% samp.ids), 
       aes(x=time, y=price)) + 
  facet_wrap(~id) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point(aes(size = all.purchases), pch=1)

set.seed(201)

samp.ids <- sample(levels(yo$id), 16)

ggplot(data=subset(yo, id %in% samp.ids), aes(x=time)) +
  facet_wrap(~id) +
  geom_point(aes(y=strawberry), color="red") +
  geom_point(aes(y=blueberry), color="blue")

The Limits of Cross Sectional Data

Notes: As in the pf data, we have no time-series data, making it “cross sectional”, or a snapshot of a larger data generating process. We can’t make across-time comparisons.
